<font color="#FF0000">THE WALL</font><br>
<tt>Thu May  8 12:23:03 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
I first visited the Wall in 1984.  I recall being incredibly nervous about doing this, although I'm not entirely certain why.  I suppose I was concerned about how I would react.  <br><br>
I remember having a friend drop me off at the Lincoln Memorial, because I wanted to do this alone.  My friend new little about those I was looking for, and I was still apprehensive about my potential reaction.<br><br>
I don't even remember how I got from the Lincoln Memorial to the Wall.  Too many thoughts racing through my mind.  It had been 14 years since leaving Nam and I was beginning to question my own memory of the events that I experienced in 1970.  I would read a book or see a movie or hear someone talking, and rarely did these communications seem real to me.  It was like they were talking about some place I had never been.<br><br>
I remember sitting on a bunker one late afternoon along the DMZ, reading a aging edition of Starts and Stripes.   One of the articles talked about Nixon and some bombing halt.  As I was reading the article, I could hear the B52's overhead heading north.  Just shook my head and wondered if Nixon had even a clue.<br><br>
It was this kind of disparity that made me leery about going to the Wall.  Did the government really get their paperwork right?  Would my friends who were supposed to be there actually make it?  Was my memory that questionable?<br><br>
I had no clue about the make up of the Wall, how to find someone.  As I strolled into the depths of this amazing concept, all I could do was wonder how I would ever find the names I was looking for.  There were so many names.  So many instances in time that affected so many people in terrible ways.<br><br>
My confusion must have been obvious.  After a while, a volunteer came up to me and asked if he could help.  It was then that it occurred to me that I wasn't completely sure I remembered the correct spelling of my friends names.  We all went by nicknames.  I was looking for Shallako and Rocky.  <br><br>
It took a moment, and I did know the day it happened.  I will never forget that part.  And the volunteer was able to locate them for me.<br><br>
There they were.  I could only stand there trembling.  Trembling, I think, at the external confirmation of my own memory.  Their names carved into that black granite wall, staring at me from about a foot away, took me hurdling back in time to one horrible day in 1970.<br><br>
I really didn't know what to do, other than rub my fingers over their names and tell them that I missed them, that I would never forget them.<br><br>
After a bit, I had to back away..  I drifted back to the point where the statue now stands and sat against a tree for a long, long time, gazing at the Wall and trying to put it in some sort of perspective.<br><br>
I'm still not sure what happened to me that day.  I was sad, I was confused, and I was happy.  Happy isn't a word I generally use in relation to Nam.  But knowing that nothing could ever bring them back, it made me happy to know that this wall would be there for a long, long time to come, and their names would stand in testimony of what happened on May 5, 1970.  It was almost as if a great burden had been taken off my shoulders.  As if I didn't have to rely on my own suspect memory to keep their story alive.<br><br>
I also was happy that I had a place that I could visit when I wanted to talk with them....and the others.  It shames me to admit that I can't remember the names of some I knew who are on that Wall, too.  For some reason, my mind always returns to Shallako and Rocky when I think about Nam.  I guess I just wasn't as close to the others that got it too.<br><br>
Who knows?  Who really knows anything about why Nam had to happen?  It did, though.  And we owe to those on the Wall to remember that it did happen.  We  owe it to the next generation to explain the unexplainable in the hopes that it won't happen again.<br><br>
The Wall goes a long way toward that end.  If you haven't been there, do yourself a favor and make the trip.  It won't be easy, I assure you.  But sometimes you gotta do what you gotta do.<br><br>
Shallako....Rocky.....tell them what happened when they walk by.  Don't let them forget.
<p><code>-- motom@coredcs.com  (Jim Morse) </code><p>


